{"parse":{"title":"The Rise of Victimhood Culture","pageid":57568964,"revid":858220303,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><br />\n<i><b>The Rise of Victimhood Culture: Microaggressions, Safe Spaces, and the New Culture Wars</b></i>, is a 2018 book by sociologists <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Bradley_Campbell_(sociologist)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Bradley Campbell (sociologist) (page does not exist)\">Bradley Campbell</a> and <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Jason_Manning&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Jason Manning (page does not exist)\">Jason Manning</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Rise_of_Victimhood_Culture&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The book began as a scholarly paper entitled <i>Microaggression and Moral Cultures</i> published in the journal <i>Comparative Sociology</i> in 2014.<sup id=\"cite_ref-CompSoc_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CompSoc-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Friedersdorf_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Friedersdorf-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Campbell and Manning argue that accusations of <a href=\"/wiki/Microaggression\" title=\"Microaggression\">microaggression</a> focus on unintentional slights, unlike the <a href=\"/wiki/Civil_rights_movement\" title=\"Civil rights movement\">Civil rights movement</a>, which focused on concrete injustices.  They argue that the purpose of calling attention to microaggressions is less to elevate the status of offended victim. \"When the victims publicize micoaggressions,\u201d wrote  Campbell and Manning \u201cthey call attention to what they see as the deviant behavior of the offenders. In doing so,\u201d they \u201calso call attention to their own victimization.\u201d   They do this because it lowers \u201cthe offender\u2019s moral status\u201d and \u201craises the moral status of the victims.\u201d<sup id=\"cite_ref-CompSoc_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CompSoc-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-BarbashCampuses_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BarbashCampuses-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-WayneAbout_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-WayneAbout-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Thesis\">Thesis</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Rise_of_Victimhood_Culture&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Thesis\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In both the paper and the book, Mason and Campbell draw on the work of sociologist <a href=\"/wiki/Donald_Black_(sociologist)\" title=\"Donald Black (sociologist)\">Donald Black</a> on conflict and on cross-cultural studies of conflict and morality to argue that the contemporary culture wars resemble tactics described by scholars in which an aggrieved party or group seeks the support of third parties.  They argue that  grievance-based conflicts ave led to large-scale moral change in which an emergent victimhood culture is clashing with and replacing older honor and dignity cultures.<sup id=\"cite_ref-CompSoc_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CompSoc-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Honour cultures, often called <a href=\"/wiki/Shame_society\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Shame society\">honour-shame cultures</a> are cultures like that of the <a href=\"/wiki/Old_west\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Old west\">old time American West</a> or Europe in the era when dueling was common.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Friedersdorf_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Friedersdorf-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  In such cultures, honour is paramount, and when it is offended, the offended party retaliated directly, by, for example, engaging in a <a href=\"/wiki/Blood_feud\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Blood feud\">blood feud</a>.  In honor cultures, victims have an extremely low moral status.<sup id=\"cite_ref-WayneAbout_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-WayneAbout-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Mason and Campbell describe honour-shame culture as having been replaced in the modern Western world in the 19th and 20th century by a dignity culture where, \u201cinsults might provoke offense, but they no longer have the same importance as a way of establishing or destroying a reputation for bravery.\u201d Instead, \u201cWhen intolerable conflicts do arise, dignity cultures prescribe direct but non-violent actions.\u201d<sup id=\"cite_ref-CompSoc_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CompSoc-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Friedersdorf_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Friedersdorf-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  In such a culture, instead of challenging the offender to a duel, an aggrieved party might \u201cexercise covert avoidance, quietly cutting off relations with the offender without any confrontation\u201d or  \u201cconceptualize the problem as a disruption to their relationship and seek only to restore harmony without passing judgment.\u201d Legal action was taken, \u201cFor offenses like theft, assault, or breach of contract, people in a dignity culture will use law without shame,... \u201cBut in keeping with their ethic of restraint and toleration, it is not necessarily their first resort, and they might condemn many uses of the authorities as frivolous. People might even be expected to tolerate serious but accidental personal injuries.\u201d<sup id=\"cite_ref-CompSoc_1-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CompSoc-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Friedersdorf_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Friedersdorf-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-HennenReview_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-HennenReview-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>A dignity culture, according to Campbell and Manning, has moral values and behavioral norms that promote the value of every human life, encouraging achievement in its children while teaching that <a href=\"/wiki/Sticks_and_Stones\" title=\"Sticks and Stones\">sticks and stones may break my bones, but words will never break me</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-CampbellReview_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CampbellReview-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Because victimhood culture now confers the highest moral status on victims, Campbell and Manning argue that it \u201cincreases the incentive to publicize grievances.\u201d  Injured and offended parties who might once have thrown a punch or filed a law suit, now  appeal for support on social media.<sup id=\"cite_ref-WayneAbout_4-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-WayneAbout-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>According to Campbell and  Manning, victimhood culture engenders \u201ccompetitive victimhood,\u201d incentivizing even privileged people to claim that they are victims of, for example <a href=\"/wiki/Reverse_discrimination\" title=\"Reverse discrimination\">reverse discrimination</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-WayneAbout_4-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-WayneAbout-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Rise_of_Victimhood_Culture&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-CompSoc-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-CompSoc_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-CompSoc_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-CompSoc_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-CompSoc_1-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-CompSoc_1-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Campbell, Bradley; Manning, Jason (2014). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://booksandjournals.brillonline.com/content/journals/10.1163/15691330-12341332\">\"Microaggression and Moral Cultures\"</a>. <i>Comparative Sociology</i>. <b>13</b> (6): 692.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Comparative+Sociology&amp;rft.atitle=Microaggression+and+Moral+Cultures&amp;rft.volume=13&amp;rft.issue=6&amp;rft.pages=692&amp;rft.date=2014&amp;rft.aulast=Campbell&amp;rft.aufirst=Bradley&amp;rft.au=Manning%2C+Jason&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fbooksandjournals.brillonline.com%2Fcontent%2Fjournals%2F10.1163%2F15691330-12341332&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+Rise+of+Victimhood+Culture\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Friedersdorf-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Friedersdorf_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Friedersdorf_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Friedersdorf_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Friedersdorf_2-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Friedersdorf, Conor (11 September 2015). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/09/the-rise-of-victimhood-culture/404794/\">\"The Rise of Victimhood Culture\"</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/The_Atlantic\" title=\"The Atlantic\">The Atlantic</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">31 May</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=The+Rise+of+Victimhood+Culture&amp;rft.date=2015-09-11&amp;rft.aulast=Friedersdorf&amp;rft.aufirst=Conor&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theatlantic.com%2Fpolitics%2Farchive%2F2015%2F09%2Fthe-rise-of-victimhood-culture%2F404794%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+Rise+of+Victimhood+Culture\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-BarbashCampuses-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-BarbashCampuses_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Barbash, Fred (28 October 2015). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/10/28/the-war-over-words-literally-on-some-american-campuses-where-asking-where-are-you-from-is-a-microaggression/\">\"The war on 'microaggressions:' Has it created a 'victimhood culture' on campuses?\"</a>. Washington Post<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">1 June</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=The+war+on+%E2%80%98microaggressions%3A%E2%80%99+Has+it+created+a+%E2%80%98victimhood+culture%E2%80%99+on+campuses%3F&amp;rft.date=2015-10-28&amp;rft.aulast=Barbash&amp;rft.aufirst=Fred&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.washingtonpost.com%2Fnews%2Fmorning-mix%2Fwp%2F2015%2F10%2F28%2Fthe-war-over-words-literally-on-some-american-campuses-where-asking-where-are-you-from-is-a-microaggression%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+Rise+of+Victimhood+Culture\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-WayneAbout-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-WayneAbo